##Rediscover my place in the fortress | Guo Jing's diary of the siege of Wuhan | 27 -- 29

Micro signal

Features an introduction to the refreshing flavor of the feminist hardcore

A sanitation worker still works on the streets of Wuhan (picture provided by Guo Jing) 

This is my friend Guo Jing's diary.

It records the real life experience and psychological feeling of the women who lived alone in Wuhan during the period of Fengcheng.

These words bear witness to Guo's journey from adapting to a sudden crisis to rebuilding her daily life to trying to help others.

After the diary was released on December 23rd, many readers left messages in the background hoping to see what would happen next. Guo Jing and I discussed after the decision to move once every three days.

Those who want to keep up to date can follow@guo Jing, a social worker, on Weibo.
There is Guo Jing's personal wechat qr code at the end of the article, you can also apply to add. She posts daily on her friends'network.
(but please don't talk to Guo Jing privately to avoid adding to her burden.)

Even though I'm trying to go further every day, what's the point of going further if I don't connect with people here?

A view of Wuhan in the Sun (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

27 January

I was paralyzed in bed for two or three hours yesterday after I finished writing my diary. I had no idea keeping a diary was such a Labor of love. This lock-up has brought time and space to a standstill, while our emotions and emotions are magnified. I've never paid so much attention to myself, and a lot of small thoughts are hard to get away with at the moment.

We usually have a lot of channels to adjust, vent or even escape their negative emotions. And in a blockade, it becomes extremely difficult. We used to be able to regulate ourselves by partying, playing games, developing hobbies, and so on, but now we can't. We can't ignore the fact that there's a huge cloud in our lives.

A gamer friend of mine recently lost her job and said she was too anxious to play games. Playing Video Games is her daily escape from life, but when the job search is so urgent that she can not escape, playing video games loses its meaning.

Lying in bed brushing his cell phone when suddenly heard the neighbors talk and laugh, feel very precious. All I see out there these days is tension and anxiety. Some people open their windows and yell, "WHO's there? Let's have a fight! " Some people say they are stuck at home with their partners and have nothing to do until they get bored.

Dinner on January 26th
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Last night's dinner was noodles. I continued to video chat with my friends for over three hours. A friend who had recently had his ear pierced lost an earring and is now afraid to go out and buy one, so he uses a tea stem as an earring. A friend in Luoyang says her dad's pretty calm, probably because he's been through a lot. Disasters seem to be an inescapable part of being human, as in 2003, when we had SARS, and in 2008, when we had the Wenchuan County earthquake.

Some people say that next Spring Festival will not change, not so many parties, do not have to and many unfamiliar relatives chat awkwardly. Others say they may retaliate with dinner parties and forced marriages. The number of blind dates that failed this year because of pneumonia may double next year.

In the evening, I had a dream that I was going on a trip with some friends. In the dream, I also had pneumonia. We were GONNA go out to dinner, and there are places that are open. I strongly object to eating in the store, suggesting we take it to go, because eating in the store requires taking off your mask. Somehow, we ended up eating at the restaurant. Last night when chatting, a friend said that after unsealing to invite me to dinner, I said to eat hot pot.

Two stray cats (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

The weather in Wuhan is a little clearer today, although it is still cloudy. A few steps out the door to see the ruins of the two cats, we looked at each other. The scene was so apocalyptic that we looked at each other as if it was just me and the two cats. Too Bad I didn't bring any food. I can go out again and take some food to feed some stray cats and dogs.

The kidney noodle shop is still doing take-out. The two wreaths in front of the wreath shop yesterday are missing today. The old man who was in the alley two days ago is not here today. The supermarket's shelves of Vegetables, Rice and flour are still scarce, and the shelves of salt are empty. There are more people waiting in line to be weighed today, perhaps to restock, perhaps just want to go out and buy something.

There were 84 in the supermarket today. I bought two 84s. Not Buying any more food made me feel that I had somehow conquered my sense of scarcity. In fact, I was worried the other day that I was saving too much, but I couldn't help it. I think it has something to do with poverty. I would get stuck at discount stores and sale sites, always trying to get the best deal at a sale, and would buy things that might not end up being used, originally to save money, but ended up being wasted.

The pharmacy still doesn't have masks or alcohol. The florist is still in the "send flowers out" state. The market was not open, but two or three people were selling vegetables from stalls.

People line up in a supermarket (photo courtesy of Guo Jing)

I made it to tenwaring today. There are people selling some vegetables at the end of the alley. Enter Tanhualin, a delicious snack shop from the smell of a man standing in front of the shop. I was pleasantly surprised to think that the store was open, so I asked. The store said it was too late to open the door. Tanhualin is a popular literary street, there are a lot of coffee shops, drink shops, jewelry shops. People could spend their free time here, but now the whole street is free.

An old man opened the window and looked out from upstairs. Tanhualin history and culture block yard from the sound of cucurbits, into the yard only those New Year decorations still. Some shops with glass wind chimes hanging in the doorway, with the wind out of the clear and crisp songs. Wind chimes hang with people's desire for work, study, love, body. Usually I would find these very sentimental, at this moment I have a lot of people in mind to write down their wishes seriously picture.

Tan Hualin's Spring Festival decorations (picture provided by Guo Jing)

Walking out of Tanhualin, I saw a box of fresh x and went in. There's a man at the door taking his temperature. The supermarket is bigger, but the vegetable stands are empty. The Spring Festival playlist is playing in the supermarket.

There was no pressure to buy anything, I just walked around and went to the self-cooking hot pot rack. Thinking that I could improve my life tonight or be lazy, I decided to spend 65.7 on a box of self-cooking hot pot and snail powder. I shook to the music as I waited for the check-out.

I like the square dance, the square dance rhythm is very strong, also quite joyful, dances the square dance the human also very energetic, lets the human look very happy. When I walked out of the supermarket, my feet became light and I sang a song.

When I walked to the door of the People's government of Wuchang District, I saw a middle-aged woman riding a yellow bicycle shouting at the door. She repeated it over and over. A couple of cars came in, security was there, no one answered. She's as transparent as a ghost.

At times like this, she insists on shouting at the government gates. This is not the first, and probably not the last, day. My mood suddenly became heavy again. Out of more than 100 meters, I still came from behind the "please lead reception" voice.

Women demanding reception from their leaders (photo courtesy of Guo Jing)

When he came to a police integrated service station, there was a loudspeaker hanging at the door, an announcer was passionately chanting, "the prevention and control station of COVID-19 infection has been set up... we stand by each other and together, we will win the battle against COVID-19 pneumonia. " . The slogan was played over and over in the empty streets, full of irony.

Back to the gate of the community, there is a man shouting: Come out to Chat Ah, to long hair. A few people were laughing nearby. I couldn't help laughing.

I can't write the whole diary in a unified mood. The world is so absurd that I can only record it all.

28 January

The blockade has created panic, and panic is deepening the separation between people. Many cities are beginning to require masks to be worn in public. This seems to be the prevention and control of pneumonia, in fact, brought about the abuse of power.

Yesterday in Guangzhou, people without masks were dragged off the subway and pepper sprayed. We don't know why they don't wear masks. Maybe they don't buy them. Maybe they don't see the need to wear masks. However, they should not be deprived of the right to go out. There are other ways to encourage people to go out less and wear masks in public places, such as making sure everyone has a mask and giving rewards to those who don't go out.

There is also a video of a group of people blocking the doors of people who are isolated at home. The hupeis were driven out of town and had nowhere to go. It's scary, and the way to deal with pneumonia is not to defend yourself. At the same time, there are people who are trying to break down barriers by offering housing to Hubei people who are out of town.

It is not easy to build trust and bonds in an embargo. Yesterday, a reporter asked me if I would consider communicating with others. I replied that I didn't know. The whole city is covered with a heavy atmosphere, in which, I do not consciously carefully up, do not dare to casual communication with people. Blockades atomize people's lives and cut them off from one another.

But people are not content with the status quo. About eight o'clock last night, the window sounded shouting, we all open the window to call "Wuhan refueling. ". The cry of the collective is a kind of self-empowerment from which people seek connection and gain strength.

People Shout "Go Wuhan" in their homes

Last night's dinner was a hot pot buffet. After dinner, I talked with my friends as usual. It is not easy to chat every day, and soon you will have nothing to say. So, we decided to take turns sharing our secrets. The Beijing Group Bcome created the Vagina Monologues (a Chinese version of the vagina monologues) with a line: "What we don't say becomes secrets, and those secrets generate shame, fear and myth. "

We talked about some unique habits, such as some people say that they do not like to take a bath, some people talk about their relationship with family, family secrets and so on. We also talked about the IQ taxes we paid, the magic goods we bought, some people bought pepper cream, claimed that can lose weight, put on the body will be hot. Of course, we inevitably talked about pneumonia, and we shared some of the information we'd seen, about some of the groups that kept the city going but were left out. I decided to understand the needs of these people.

My survival anxiety has eased over the last few days. Even though I'm trying to go further every day, what's the point of going further if I don't connect with the people here? Social participation is an important demand of human beings. People need to have their own social role in society, can play their social value, to give meaning to their lives.

I will find my place in this city again. Even though I don't have a lot of resources and contacts in this city, and I don't have a car, I'm limited in my space. But yesterday I saw someone riding a shared bike, and I thought I could go for a bike ride.

Dinner on January 27th
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Today, the weather in Wuhan is finally sunny, just like my mood. Out of the community to see more people, there are two or three community workers, they seem to be doing the screening, said to check the outsiders. I asked one of the older women if they had hair masks. She said no, and another man rushed over to say yes.

Then I interviewed eight sanitation workers, six women and two men. They work about seven or eight hours a day, get paid about two thousand and four, and less than $2,000 after taxes.

I asked if there would be any change in their wages during the pneumonia period. Some people said that three days during the Spring Festival were double wages. Some people didn't know at all.

They now receive 84 disinfectants a day, reusable protective gloves, no disposable gloves, and a wide range of surgical masks. Those in good condition can get 20 masks at a time, and those in the worst condition can only get 2 masks since they were sealed off.

They were kind people, some of whom didn't have disposable surgical masks and wrapped their mouths in scarves. I gave away three disposable surgical masks I had on hand when I went out. One of them spoke with an accent, which sounded laborious to me, and one older sister couldn't resist taking off her mask and putting it back on quickly. Some people prepare their own masks, said, "for family, for everyone, for the country. ".

I asked if their families were worried. One older sister said she must be worried. She was already separated from her son and daughter-in-law. They didn't go out. She would buy things and bring them to the door.

They work for a small salary, with no basic protection. Are we really worth it?

A sanitation worker's Glove (picture provided by Guo Jing)

I also spoke to three delivery boys, all male. Take-out workers, who work irregular hours, are almost always outfitted with face masks, at least two a day, and sterilize their boxes every day. The x-ball delivery guy also dispenses hand sanitizer.

When I asked if I would get a pay raise, they said the takeout category was more complicated, depending on the supplier, the weight of the goods, etc. . X Group delivery would cost 3.50 yuan more than usual; one x group delivery man said he would get 4 yuan more than usual, and another said there was no change.

I also went to a convenience store, open at 5:00 a.m. , close at 11:00 p.m. , a day issued an N95 mask, relatively alcohol shortage, now mainly to accept the x order.

I'm GonNa make myself a connection. So I put out my own Wechat Qr code, welcome everyone to add me. If you are in Wuhan and want to help break the blockade, we can do something together for the neglected groups. If you are out of town and want to donate some masks and other necessary materials, you can send them to me, i can go out and give it to whoever I need. Let's form a network together.

A corner of the supermarket (picture provided by Guo Jing)

29 January

At the end of 2017, I launched the 074 workplace women's legal hotline, which provides legal support to women who experience gender discrimination in the workplace. Yesterday afternoon, I got a pregnancy discrimination call. The caller was a man whose wife, Ms. Pan, was an executive at a state-owned enterprise. Ms Poon, who joined the company in July 1919, is three months pregnant.

Pan's pregnancy reaction is quite big, the vomit is quite severe, the doctor recommends the rest. Because of repeated leave, the company began to say that she was not suitable for the job, suggesting that she leave. Ms. Pan is under a lot of stress. Since the company has not yet told her to leave, I can only recommend that she continue to work and collect evidence of discrimination. As luck would have it, Ms. Pan and her husband are now in Wuhan, too, and they have stockpiled some food. I hope we'll have a chance to meet when the seal is lifted.

Work is a concern for many people now. The Lunar New Year holiday is now extended to February 2, but if the epidemic continues to spread, people will not be able to return to work in peace. Big companies may have enough money to keep going, and extended holidays can take a heavy toll on small businesses and self-employed workers, who may not make much money, face pressure to pay rent, and may be laid off. Women are often the first to be laid off in job cuts.

Individuals, some of whom are under pressure to get a mortgage and some of whom have families to take care of, may be thinking about taking a risk to go to work. How To solve these problems? Ultimately, the state has to take on these responsibilities, cutting taxes for businesses and providing basic living allowances for individuals.

Dinner on January 28th
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Yesterday I got a message from a high school friend I haven't talked to in years. She's a nurse now. She said: "I read every one of your diary, I can not think of any more words to comfort you, my heart is full of heaviness, I just want to tell you, I submitted to the unit today to apply to the front line of the request, if possible, I would like to go there and fight with you, you are not alone, the pace of national civilization is getting closer and closer, there may still be some places not perfect, but please do not forget to love and hope. ". In my mind you are still that thin and stubborn you, I believe you will be able to safely return in this epidemic."

After reading it, I was moved to tears. (PS: I'm not skinny now.)

Last night's dinner was rice porridge with celery and fried chicken breast. In the evening, I continued to video chat with my friends. The friend who didn't like to bathe hadn't bathed for more than a week, so she decided to take a bath the next day. Guangzhou's celery ten yuan a catty, Beijing friends bought five potatoes, big and small, spent more than a dozen. A friend began to listen to detective story, let oneself and pneumonia information have a short separation, adjust the state.

We talked about what could be done for sanitation workers, and there was a proposal to issue guidelines on how to wear a mask, and given the situation of sanitation workers, some of them might not be able to read. I had a printer, and now it's broken. Two of my online friends donated money to me and asked me to transfer it to the sanitation worker. I'm just GONNA talk to everybody about raising money for the garbage man.

I'm just an individual, and it's hard to guarantee transparency and credibility, and I'm not qualified to manage donations. I'll donate what I've already collected, and I won't take any more donations to the sanitation workers. And that's not necessarily what they need right now. It's easier for us to donate in a way, and harder for us to really care about their lives.

A corner of the supermarket (picture provided by Guo Jing)

The weather is still fine today. I woke up at 7:00 in the morning. I was so sleepy, I went back to sleep. And then I dozed off until almost 10:00. When I got up, I did my usual exercise. Last night a friend sent me the contact information of the volunteer team of Wuhan Logistics Association. After breakfast, I contacted them to see if I could help.

I want to talk to the garbage man more today. The first street sweeper I met when I went out was the big sister who was going to give something to her son and daughter-in-law yesterday. At first, she was a little defensive. She asked me what I did and why. I said I was just a volunteer, trying to get to know and document the life of a sanitation worker. She still doesn't understand. She told me not to take pictures, not to record anything, not to give her name. She was an old Wuhan Native who spoke with an accent, some of which I did not fully understand, and which I could not record.

Big sister is very talkative. She worked as a sanitation worker for more than a year. She worked as an accountant in a factory before retiring at the age of 45. Now the unit no longer for her social security. I mean, what if she's sick? She says she's fine. She had one day off a week, she had never taken a day off from work, and she cleaned the streets, rain or shine, heat or cold. Standing 99% of the day. Standing up all day, my legs are sore at night. Sometimes when I get home, I don't even want to do the laundry or cook.

Her area is about 500 meters down the street. Big Sister said that in addition to cleaning time, the sanitation workers in a hidden corner to observe their jurisdiction, where dirty immediately go to clean up, if not cleaning people generally do not see them.

Her husband has been dead for years, and she has a son. Son Got Heart disease, the year before last in the hospital in Guangzhou for surgery, now also take medicine, a month to pieces of medical expenses. Son Health is not good, can choose the work is also limited, began to rent a car to drive Didi, sometimes a few days to rest a few days, income is not stable. The elder sister's salary not only guarantees own life, sometimes also must subsidize the son.

A sanitation worker still works on the streets of Wuhan (picture provided by Guo Jing) 

Each sanitation worker has his or her own area of responsibility and can not talk to colleagues in the adjacent area during breaks. Big sister doesn't talk all day. She often meets people who ask for directions, many of whom are not polite. Some motorist beckoned her over from afar. A person who asked the way after asking big sister, and asked others, big sister said he clearly pointed the way is right, the man came back to accuse her, also said "you can only do sanitation workers. ". So sometimes she doesn't even want to respond to people asking for directions, she says she's not obligated to give directions, she's just being nice, and they take it for granted. She said that loneliness and lack of respect are debilitating.

After the city was shut down, she continued to work in order to survive. She goes to work at 11:00 every day and leaves at 6:00. The local supermarket doesn't open until 10:00. She said she can not buy food to take to work, can only after work to buy food, some of the food prices, can buy very little food. Luckily there was a hotel nearby that sold some vegetables cheaply. She bought some potatoes and cauliflower. She spent $198 on 100 masks, only to have them stolen during her break.

Before I left, I left some masks for my sister. She said thank you. I can find her on that road. Well, I don't think I'm good enough for her thanks.

In my opinion, her story is an indictment, an indictment of social injustice, an indictment of discrimination and arrogance.

I released the Qr Code on wechat yesterday, hoping to connect with more people and act together. Someone said the Qr Code Wasn't working. If you have the same situation, you can add me through the micro signal, my micro signal: 1461177244.

28 January

The blockade has created panic, and panic is deepening the separation between people. Many cities are beginning to require masks to be worn in public. This seems to be the prevention and control of pneumonia, in fact, brought about the abuse of power.

Yesterday in Guangzhou, people without masks were dragged off the subway and pepper sprayed. We don't know why they don't wear masks. Maybe they don't buy them. Maybe they don't see the need to wear masks. However, they should not be deprived of the right to go out. There are other ways to encourage people to go out less and wear masks in public places, such as making sure everyone has a mask and giving rewards to those who don't go out.

There is also a video of a group of people blocking the doors of people who are isolated at home. The hupeis were driven out of town and had nowhere to go. It's scary, and the way to deal with pneumonia is not to defend yourself. At the same time, there are people who are trying to break down barriers by offering housing to Hubei people who are out of town.

It is not easy to build trust and bonds in an embargo. Yesterday, a reporter asked me if I would consider communicating with others. I replied that I didn't know. The whole city is covered with a heavy atmosphere, in which, I do not consciously carefully up, do not dare to casual communication with people. Blockades atomize people's lives and cut them off from one another.

But people are not content with the status quo. About eight o'clock last night, the window sounded shouting, we all open the window to call "Wuhan refueling. ". The cry of the collective is a kind of self-empowerment from which people seek connection and gain strength.

Today, the weather in Wuhan is finally sunny, just like my mood. Out of the community to see more people, there are two or three community workers, they seem to be doing the screening, said to check the outsiders. Then I interviewed eight sanitation workers, six women and two men. They work about seven or eight hours a day, get paid about two thousand and four, and less than $2,000 after taxes.

I asked if there would be any change in their wages during the pneumonia period. Some people said that three days during the Spring Festival were double wages. Some people didn't know at all.

They now receive 84 disinfectants a day, reusable protective gloves, no disposable gloves, and a wide range of surgical masks. Those in good condition can get 20 masks at a time, and those in the worst condition can only get 2 masks since they were sealed off.

They were kind people, some of whom didn't have disposable surgical masks and wrapped their mouths in scarves. I gave away three disposable surgical masks I had on hand when I went out. One of them spoke with an accent, which sounded laborious to me, and one older sister couldn't resist taking off her mask and putting it back on quickly. Some people prepare their own masks, said, "for family, for everyone, for the country. ".

I asked if their families were worried. One older sister said she must be worried. She was already separated from her son and daughter-in-law. They didn't go out. She would buy things and bring them to the door.

They work for a small salary, with no basic protection. Are we really worth it?

29 January

At the end of 2017, I launched the 074 workplace women's legal hotline, which provides legal support to women who experience gender discrimination in the workplace. Yesterday afternoon, I got a pregnancy discrimination call. The caller was a man whose wife, Ms. Pan, was an executive at a state-owned enterprise. Ms Poon, who joined the company in July 1919, is three months pregnant.

Pan's pregnancy reaction is quite big, the vomit is quite severe, the doctor recommends the rest. Because of repeated leave, the company began to say that she was not suitable for the job, suggesting that she leave. Ms. Pan is under a lot of stress. Since the company has not yet told her to leave, I can only recommend that she continue to work and collect evidence of discrimination. As luck would have it, Ms. Pan and her husband are now in Wuhan, too, and they have stockpiled some food. I hope we'll have a chance to meet when the seal is lifted.

Work is a concern for many people now. The Lunar New Year holiday is now extended to February 2, but if the epidemic continues to spread, people will not be able to return to work in peace. Big companies may have enough money to keep going, and extended holidays can take a heavy toll on small businesses and self-employed workers, who may not make much money, face pressure to pay rent, and may be laid off. Women are often the first to be laid off in job cuts.

Individuals, some of whom are under pressure to get a mortgage and some of whom have families to take care of, may be thinking about taking a risk to go to work. How To solve these problems? Ultimately, the state has to take on these responsibilities, cutting taxes for businesses and providing basic living allowances for individuals.
